The proposed function puts the use case in the wrong place. `NextRequest`, `NextResponse`, Prisma models, and Prisma queries are all outer-layer details, but the approval rule and invoice-creation action are core policy. The smallest production shape is: one use case, plain application-owned models, two inward-owned ports, thin adapters, and wiring at the edge.

A minimal design:

```ts
// invoice/application/create-invoice.ts
export type CreateInvoiceInput = {
  orderId: string;
};

export type CreateInvoiceOutput = {
  invoiceId: string;
  totalCents: number;
};

export type OrderForInvoicing = {
  id: string;
  status: "APPROVED" | "PENDING" | "CANCELLED";
  lines: Array<{ amountCents: number }>;
};

export type InvoiceToSave = {
  orderId: string;
  totalCents: number;
};

export interface LoadOrderForInvoicing {
  load(orderId: string): Promise<OrderForInvoicing | null>;
}

export interface SaveInvoice {
  save(invoice: InvoiceToSave): Promise<{ id: string }>;
}

export class OrderNotApprovedError extends Error {}
export class OrderNotFoundError extends Error {}

export class CreateInvoice {
  constructor(
    private readonly loadOrder: LoadOrderForInvoicing,
    private readonly saveInvoice: SaveInvoice,
  ) {}

  async execute(input: CreateInvoiceInput): Promise<CreateInvoiceOutput> {
    const order = await this.loadOrder.load(input.orderId);
    if (!order) throw new OrderNotFoundError();
    if (order.status !== "APPROVED") throw new OrderNotApprovedError();

    const totalCents = order.lines.reduce((sum, line) => sum + line.amountCents, 0);
    const saved = await this.saveInvoice.save({ orderId: order.id, totalCents });

    return { invoiceId: saved.id, totalCents };
  }
}
```

Ownership and placement:
- Application layer owns `CreateInvoiceInput`, `CreateInvoiceOutput`, `LoadOrderForInvoicing`, `SaveInvoice`, and the `CreateInvoice` use case.
- The order snapshot used by this use case can stay application-owned because it exists only to support this action.
- Next.js route owns HTTP parsing and HTTP response mapping.
- Prisma adapters own database queries and Prisma model translation.
- Composition root / outer infrastructure owns construction of `CreateInvoice` with Prisma-backed adapters.

Translation points:
- In the Next.js handler: `NextRequest` query param -> `CreateInvoiceInput`; use-case result/errors -> HTTP JSON/status.
- In the Prisma order adapter: Prisma row graph -> `OrderForInvoicing`.
- In the Prisma invoice adapter: `InvoiceToSave` -> Prisma `create`; Prisma result -> `{ id: string }`.

Concrete wiring belongs in outer infrastructure, for example:

```ts
// invoice/infrastructure/wiring.ts
export function makeCreateInvoice() {
  return new CreateInvoice(
    new PrismaLoadOrderForInvoicing(prisma),
    new PrismaSaveInvoice(prisma),
  );
}
```

Then the route is just an adapter:

```ts
// app/api/invoices/route.ts
export async function POST(request: NextRequest) {
  const useCase = makeCreateInvoice();

  try {
    const result = await useCase.execute({
      orderId: request.nextUrl.searchParams.get("orderId")!,
    });
    return NextResponse.json(result, { status: 201 });
  } catch (error) {
    if (error instanceof OrderNotFoundError) {
      return NextResponse.json({ error: "order not found" }, { status: 404 });
    }
    if (error instanceof OrderNotApprovedError) {
      return NextResponse.json({ error: "not approved" }, { status: 409 });
    }
    throw error;
  }
}
```

This is the smallest design that preserves the required rule and action independence:
- core policy does not import Next.js or Prisma
- ports are owned inward
- adapters only translate
- concrete construction stays at the edge
